The paper deals with the combinatorial and geometric properties of planar graphs, specifically their edge crossings and straight line plane drawings. This suggests that the paper could belong to the computational geometry (cs.CG) or discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the computational complexity of finding an optimum sequence of shifts, which falls under the computational complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. The paper also mentions bounds on the obfuscation complexity of planar graphs, which could be of interest to researchers in the graph theory (cs.DS) and graph algorithms (cs.GT) sub-categories.
